Autonomous Game Dev Agent — Architecture Concept

  What It Is

  A fully autonomous AI agent (Claude Code + Godot MCP) that can implement game logic features end-to-end without human intervention, running in an isolated Docker container.

  The Stack

  - Godot 4.x — the game engine and editor
  - hi-godot MCP plugin — bridge between Claude and the Godot editor (read/write scenes, nodes, scripts, run scenes, read logs)
  - Claude Code (--dangerously-skip-permissions) — the agent, fully autonomous, no approval prompts
  - Xvfb — virtual display so Godot editor runs headless inside Docker
  - x11vnc — optional layer on top of Xvfb for live human observation
  - Docker — isolation boundary; agent has full permissions inside the container, zero blast radius outside

  The Autonomous Loop

  write/patch script
        ↓
  run scene
        ↓
  read logs (errors, print output)
        ↓
  fix issues
        ↓
  run GUT tests
        ↓
  read test results
        ↓
  take screenshot / record video as proof
        ↓
  done — human reviews artifacts

  What It's Good For

  Game logic oriented tasks that don't require visual judgment: player/NPC behaviours, state machines, combat systems, inventory, input handling, scene transitions, animation states, signal
  wiring.

  What It's Not Good For

  Shader authoring, UI layout polish, physics feel tuning — anything that requires eyes to evaluate.

  The Proof-of-Work Idea

  The agent doesn't just ship code — it produces evidence. Screenshots and short ffmpeg recordings saved to a /proof folder, captured autonomously during test runs. You review artifacts, not
  process.
